transcripts.transcript: So we have discussed the importance of understanding who we are dealing with and what is involved in your company's transactions. Let's now shift our focus to how your export activity is conducted. You might think that knowing which transactions and activities involve exports is relatively straightforward. People often think of an export as the act of taking or shipping goods across a border from one country to another country. In fact, this is only one of many ways that governments consider transactions to be exports for purposes of export controls. You might not even be aware when your actions constitute an export. Exports for purposes of export controls can occur in several different ways. As mentioned, an export occurs when you ship or take goods, so-called tangible items from one country to another. Examples of tangible exports include not only products we ship to customers but also a paper document containing controlled information carried in a briefcase, a laptop containing controlled software or technical information carried in a car or on an airplane, a USB storage device containing controlled information in a laptop or in your pocket and a smartphone containing controlled information. Exports also occur in intangible form So it is also an export to transfer software and technology from one country to another country. Examples of intangible exports include transferring controlled information through any electronic means such as email, fax, phone or video conference to entities or people outside your home country, accessing controlled information on the company network or other company servers from remote locations, uploading controlled information onto shared FTP or other remote file sharing sites and performing maintenance or training on controlled items. In another country, governments around the world have regulations that define how physical and intangible items are allowed to transit across international borders and among people of different nationalities. In summary, there are three important steps to understanding the how for any export transaction. First, you should engage your international trade compliance personnel to determine whether an export authorization is required for your transaction. Because the process for applying for government authorizations can be quite complex and time consuming. It is imperative that you engage your company's international trade compliance department as soon as possible. Even as early as the product design phase. Finally, your company must maintain accurate records of all export transactions. Such records include but are not limited to physical records of shipment, paperwork such as commercial invoices, air waybills and bills of lading for intangible items. You must follow your company's procedures for maintaining records involving emails FTP transactions or other electronic transfers.
